  "content": "<div class=\"prose prose-lg max-w-none\">\n        <p>Most dental insurance plans consider porcelain veneers a cosmetic treatment, so they usually are not covered. That can feel discouraging if you are eager to refresh your smile, but there are still ways to plan for the investment and explore partial coverage.</p>\n        <p>Insurance may help when veneers are part of a larger restoration. If a tooth is cracked or weakened, your plan might contribute toward a crown. In certain situations we can design a crown that blends with nearby veneers, giving you a beautiful result while using your benefits wisely. Keep in mind that insurers often cover only a percentage of the fee and limit benefits to about $1,500–$2,000 per year.</p>\n        <p>Quality matters. Lower-cost veneers often rely on materials that chip or stain quickly, which can lead to repairs or replacements. We partner with experienced cosmetic labs that craft durable porcelain so you can enjoy long-lasting results.</p>\n        <p>If insurance will not cover the treatment, we can still help you map out a budget. Many patients choose flexible payment plans, health savings accounts, or phased treatment to make the cost comfortable.</p>\n        <p>The best first step is a consultation. We will review your goals, examine your teeth, and give you a precise estimate. From there we can talk through insurance questions, financing options, and timing so you feel confident moving forward.</p>\n      </div>",
