  "title": "Dental Veneers vs. Bonding: A Comprehensive Comparison for Your Smile Makeover",
  "slug": "dental-veneers-vs-bonding-a-comprehensive-comparison-for-your-smile-makeover",
  "excerpt": "Bonding and porcelain veneers both improve the look of your teeth, but they differ in how they are made, how long they last, and the types of concerns they solve.  Here is a simple breakdown to help you decide.",
  "content": "<div class=\"prose prose-lg max-w-none\">\n        <p>Bonding and porcelain veneers both improve the look of your teeth, but they differ in how they are made, how long they last, and the types of concerns they solve. Here is a simple breakdown to help you decide.</p>\n        <p>Bonding uses tooth-colored resin that we shape directly on your teeth and harden with a special light. It works well for small fixes—like a chip, a gap between two teeth, or a single discolored spot. Bonding is usually completed in one visit and is budget-friendly. Because the material is porous, it can stain over time and may need touch-ups every few years.</p>\n        <p>Veneers are thin porcelain shells made in a lab. They cover the entire front of the tooth and can change the color, shape, and alignment all at once. Veneers are more durable than bonding and resist stains, making them a long-term option for a full smile makeover. Treatment takes a few visits so we can design, try in, and bond the final porcelain precisely.</p>\n        <p>Many patients choose bonding for minor repairs and veneers for broader transformations. Sometimes we combine both—bonding for a quick tweak and veneers for the teeth that need a bigger change.</p>\n        <p>During your consultation we will look at your teeth, talk through your goals, and explain the cost, timeline, and care for each option. That way you can choose the solution that keeps you smiling with confidence.</p>\n      </div>",
