  "id": "dental-veneers-vs-crowns",
  "title": "Dental Veneers vs Crowns",
  "slug": "dental-veneers-vs-crowns",
  "excerpt": "Veneers and crowns are both made from beautiful, tooth-colored materials, but they serve different purposes.  Knowing the difference helps you protect your teeth and choose the right treatment.",
  "content": "<div class=\"prose prose-lg max-w-none\">\n        <p>Veneers and crowns are both made from beautiful, tooth-colored materials, but they serve different purposes. Knowing the difference helps you protect your teeth and choose the right treatment.</p>\n        <p>Veneers cover only the front side of a tooth. We recommend them when the tooth is healthy but needs cosmetic improvements—like fixing worn edges, stubborn discoloration, or small gaps. A veneer leaves most of your tooth structure in place and refreshes the outer appearance.</p>\n        <p>A crown wraps around the entire tooth. It is the best choice when a tooth is cracked, heavily filled, or has been treated with a root canal. The crown adds strength and shields the tooth from further damage, all while matching your smile.</p>\n        <p>Both treatments usually take two or three visits. We begin with a consultation and digital scans, then prepare the tooth and place a temporary restoration. Once the final porcelain returns from the lab, we bond it in place and adjust your bite so everything feels comfortable.</p>\n        <p>Insurance often helps with crowns because they restore function. Veneers are generally considered cosmetic and may not be covered. We will review your benefits and outline costs before treatment begins.</p>\n        <p>Sometimes a smile makeover includes both veneers and crowns, especially when some teeth need repair and others just need a cosmetic boost. During your visit we will map out every option so you can move forward with confidence.</p>\n      </div>",
