  "id": "how-oral-health-problems-can-affect-your-overall-health",
  "title": "How Oral Health Problems can Affect Your Overall Health",
  "slug": "how-oral-health-problems-can-affect-your-overall-health",
  "excerpt": "Your mouth is connected to the rest of your body.  When teeth or gums are inflamed, harmful bacteria can enter the bloodstream and strain the heart, lungs, and immune system.",
  "content": "<div class=\"prose prose-lg max-w-none\">\n        <p>Your mouth is connected to the rest of your body. When teeth or gums are inflamed, harmful bacteria can enter the bloodstream and strain the heart, lungs, and immune system. Research links gum disease with heart disease, stroke, diabetes complications, and respiratory infections.</p>\n        <p>That is why daily brushing, flossing, and routine cleanings matter. They remove the plaque that causes inflammation before it has a chance to travel. If you notice bleeding gums, persistent bad breath, loose teeth, or sores that do not heal, schedule a dental visit right away—those signs often point to bigger health concerns.</p>\n        <p>Supporting your oral health also means eating a balanced diet, staying hydrated, and quitting tobacco. These habits strengthen your teeth, keep saliva flowing, and protect your overall well-being.</p>\n        <p>Need help building a healthier routine? Our team can create a personalized plan, provide gentle cleanings, and screen for early signs of disease so you can stay well from head to toe.</p>\n        <p>Proper oral care is more than just supporting a stunning smile. Your teeth can indicate a variety of health concerns that most don’t even think about. Did you know that neglecting your teeth and gums poses a risk to your oral and overall health? This can potentially cause issues or increase your risk for conditions that you might expect to be unrelated.</p>\n        <h2>Health Issues Caused or Exacerbated by Poor Oral Health</h2>\n        <p>Heart attack Stroke Osteoporosis Rheumatoid Arthritis Pneumonia Spread of Infection When problems arise, scheduling an appointment with a renovative dentist such as Dr. Alexie Aguil in West Hollywood can help you get to the root of the problem. Dr. Aguil and his team at Exquisite Dentistry will work out what the next steps are in your treatment plan and put you on the right track to achieve oral wellness.</p>\n        <h2>Healthy Teeth, Better Bones</h2>\n        <p>Many of us dread going to the dentist and put off our appointments until tooth decay has already set in. Would you do the same when it comes to visiting your cardiologist for acute chest pain? The answer is most likely “no”.</p>\n        <p>Unfortunately, oral health isn’t always a priority when it should be. People suffer through sensitive, cracked teeth every day without realizing a beautiful smile isn’t all that’s at stake. Teeth with damage or decay are at risk of infection or inflammation, which can affect your jaw and compromise the bone. Osteoporosis is a real threat for patients with weakened bone structures caused by oral health problems.</p>\n        <p>Cracked, injured teeth don’t repair themselves over time, meaning it’s up to you to take the initiative and seek treatment. Good oral and overall health are two forms of preventative care that can also give you beautiful teeth. Knowing your mouth like you know your body and learning how to take care of it is important for maintaining a fulfilling lifestyle and feeling good about it.</p>\n        <h2>Problems in Your Mouth, Problems Overall</h2>\n        <p>Most of us tend to take the words “heart condition” or “lung disease” more seriously than “periodontal disease,” despite strong evidence that oral health and heart health are interlinked. We take daily measures to prevent heart and lung disease from impacting our quality of life. Why shouldn’t we do the same for our oral health?</p>\n        <p>Our mouths are entry points for the different types of infection and bacteria we encounter every day. Oral health problems can be quick to develop in the teeth and gums where proper care and protection hasn’t been provided. From there, inflammation and bacteria can travel to other parts of the body and turn into a life-threatening problem affecting your oral and overall health.</p>\n        <p>When bacteria from infected teeth or gums enters the bloodstream, the results can be devastating. Poor oral health can cause heart attacks and stroke due to bacterial collecting in the arteries. If bacteria are in the lungs, it can turn into pneumonia.</p>\n        <p>Oral health problems can also help diagnose other unknown issues affecting the rest of the body. Patients suffering from HIV/AIDS can develop sores in their mouths as a side effect of immunodeficiency. Blood diseases and diabetes also impact your teeth and gums by weakening your body’s ability to fight infection, therefore increasing your risk of periodontal disease.</p>\n        <h2>Restore Your Smile’s Brilliance</h2>\n        <p>With your smile the best it’s ever looked, your confidence will be at an all-time high CONTACT EXQUISITE DENTISTRY (323) 272-2388 Call to schedule your cosmetic dentist appointment and experience true luxury.</p>\n        <h2>A Healthy Diet Affects Oral and Overall Health</h2>\n        <p>Healthy eating and drinking also play a role in preventative care when it comes to problems with oral health. Due to the sugar content in most alcoholic beverages, patients who consume alcohol in moderation are less likely to develop periodontal diseases, stained teeth, or blood sugar disorders. Avoiding overindulgence with junk food is good for your teeth and your waistline.</p>\n        <h2>Minding Your Oral Health</h2>\n        <p>Preventative care and early treatments for oral and overall health problems are far better than waiting and addressing the problem when it might be too late.</p>\n        <h2>Knowing</h2>\n        <p>the signs for early oral cancer are important, but consulting professionals and having regular oral cancer screenings can help spot what our eyes cannot. If you’re a smoker, quitting is another healthy habit to pick up.</p>\n        <p>Female smokers are at a greater risk of developing oral cancer, which can go on to spread and affect their overall health. But it isn’t just tobacco smokers in danger: people who use marijuana are also more likely to develop severe oral health problems as well.</p>\n        <p>When you brush and floss properly, you’re removing food particles and bacteria that could otherwise build into plaque or tartar. Brushing twice a day for two minutes each can greatly reduce your chances of developing oral health problems. Getting an electric toothbrush and finding time to floss are two easy things you can add to your routine. Check out these 5 tips for improving oral care , even on a workday.</p>\n        <p>Even with daily care, schedule regular teeth cleanings . Consistent visits with dental professionals who can recognize early signs of oral health problems are the most efficient way to stay on top of your overall health.</p>\n        <h2>Healthy is Beautiful</h2>\n        <p>With so much depending on your mouth, you need to find a world-class dentist to help maintain your healthy lifestyle. For patients looking for a dental experience that feels less like a doctor’s appointment and more like a spa treatment in Los Angeles, see Dr. Alexie Aguil and his team at Exquisite Dentistry. Enjoy a range of dental services that comprehensively care for your oral and overall health in a comfortable and relaxing environment.</p>\n        <p>A beautiful smile starts with a healthy one. Contact Dr. Alexie Aguil and his team at Exquisite Dentistry. Call us at (323) 272-2388, or reach us via our website to schedule your first appointment.</p>\n      </div>",
